a) Pharaoh Necho
b) Shishak
c) Taharqa
d) Rameses II

187. According to 2 Chronicles 12:5, Shemaiah the prophet came to Rehoboam and the princes of Judah who had gathered in Jerusalem because of Shishak. He said, “Thus says the Lord, ‘You have abandoned me, so I have abandoned you to the hand of Shishak.’” What was the response of the king and princes?
a) They fought back
b) They humbled themselves and said, “The Lord is righteous”
c) They fled
d) They offered sacrifices

188. According to 2 Chronicles 12:7-8, the Lord said, “They have humbled themselves; I will not destroy them, but they shall be servants to Shishak, that they may know my service and the service of the kingdoms of the countries.” The result was that Shishak carried away the treasures of the house of the Lord and the king’s house, including what?
a) The ark of the covenant
b) The golden shields Solomon had made
c) The bronze altar
d) The temple pillars

2 Chronicles 13 — Abijah’s Victory over Jeroboam
189. According to 2 Chronicles 13:4-5, Abijah (king of Judah) stood on Mount Zemaraim and said to Jeroboam and all Israel: “Ought you not to know that the Lord God of Israel gave the kingship over Israel forever to David and his sons by a covenant of salt?” A “covenant of salt” means what?
a) A temporary covenant
b) A lasting and binding covenant
c) A covenant of peace
d) A sacrificial covenant

190. According to 2 Chronicles 13:9, Abijah accused Israel of driving out the priests of the Lord and making priests for themselves like the peoples of other lands. Anyone who came with a young bull and seven rams could become a priest of what?
a) Baal
b) Not-gods (false gods)
c) The golden calf
d) The high places

191. According to 2 Chronicles 13:12, Abijah said, “Behold, God is with us at our head, and his priests with their battle trumpets to sound the call of battle against you. O sons of Israel, do not fight against the Lord, the God of your fathers; for you cannot succeed.” What happened in the battle?
a) Judah fled
b) Jeroboam ambushed Judah
c) God defeated Jeroboam and Israel before Judah
d) The battle was a draw

192. According to 2 Chronicles 13:21, Abijah grew mighty and took how many wives?
a) 4
b) 10
c) 14
d) 20

2 Chronicles 14 — Asa’s Reforms and Victory
193. According to 2 Chronicles 14:2-4, Asa did what was good and right in the eyes of the Lord. He removed the foreign altars and high places, broke down the pillars, cut down the Asherim, and commanded Judah to seek the Lord and keep the law. This was during his reign in what city?
a) Hebron
b) Jerusalem
c) Bethlehem
d) Beersheba

194. According to 2 Chronicles 14:9, Zerah the Ethiopian (Cushite) came out against Asa with an army of how many men?
a) 100,000
b) 500,000
c) 1,000,000
d) 2,000,000

195. According to 2 Chronicles 14:11, Asa cried to the Lord his God, “Lord, there is none like you to help, between the mighty and the weak. Help us, O Lord our God, for we rely on you, and in your name we have come against this multitude. O Lord, you are our God; let no man prevail against you.” The result was what?
a) Asa fled
b) The Lord defeated the Ethiopians
c) Asa made a treaty
d) The Ethiopians retreated voluntarily

196. According to 2 Chronicles 14:13, Asa and his army pursued the Ethiopians as far as Gerar. The Ethiopians fell so that no survivors remained. They carried away much booty. What did they also destroy near Gerar?
a) The cities round about Gerar
b) The temple of Baal
c) The high places
d) The idols

2 Chronicles 15 — Azariah’s Prophecy and Asa’s Covenant
197. According to 2 Chronicles 15:1-2, the Spirit of God came upon Azariah the son of Oded. He went out to meet Asa and said, “Hear me, Asa, and all Judah and Benjamin: The Lord is with you while you are with him. If you seek him, he will be found by you, but if you forsake him, he will forsake you.” How long had Israel been without the true God and without a teaching priest and without law?
a) 10 years
b) 20 years
c) Many days (a long time)
d) 100 years

198. According to 2 Chronicles 15:8, when Asa heard these words, he took courage and put away the abominable idols from all the land of Judah, Benjamin, and from the cities he had taken in the hill country of Ephraim. He also repaired what?
a) The walls of Jerusalem
b) The altar of the Lord
c) The temple of the Lord
d) The city gates

199. According to 2 Chronicles 15:12-13, Asa and the people entered into a covenant to seek the Lord, the God of their fathers, with all their heart and soul. Whoever would not seek the Lord was to be put to death, whether small or great, man or woman. How many days did they swear this oath with shouting and trumpets?
a) 1 day
b) 3 days
c) 7 days
d) 10 days

200. According to 2 Chronicles 15:16, Asa removed Maacah his mother from being queen mother because she had made an abominable image for Asherah. Asa cut down her image, crushed it, and burned it at what place?
a) The temple gate
b) The Kidron Valley
c) Mount Zion
d) The king’s palace

