Here is the completion of the 300-question set for 1 & 2 Chronicles (RSV) with chapter and verse references — questions first, then answers separated at the end.

PART 1 — OBJECTIVE QUESTIONS (201–285)
2 Chronicles 16 — Asa’s Later Years and Failure
201. According to 2 Chronicles 16:1, in the thirty-sixth year of Asa’s reign, Baasha king of Israel went up against Judah and built Ramah to prevent anyone from going out or coming in to Asa king of Judah. Where was Ramah located?
a) Near Jerusalem
b) In the hill country of Ephraim
c) On the border of Israel and Judah
d) Near Jericho

202. According to 2 Chronicles 16:2-3, Asa took silver and gold from the treasuries of the house of the Lord and the king’s house and sent them to Ben-hadad king of Syria, saying, “Let there be a treaty between me and you, as between my father and your father. Behold, I am sending you silver and gold; go, break your treaty with Baasha king of Israel, that he may withdraw from me.” What did Asa fail to do?
a) Seek the Lord’s help
b) Consult the prophets
c) Prepare for war
d) Repent of his sins

203. According to 2 Chronicles 16:7, Hanani the seer came to Asa and said, “Because you relied on the king of Syria and did not rely on the Lord your God, the army of the king of Syria has escaped from your hand. Were not the Ethiopians and the Libyans a huge army with very many chariots and horsemen? Yet because you relied on the Lord, he gave them into your hand. For the eyes of the Lord run to and fro throughout the whole earth to show his might on behalf of those whose heart is what?”
a) Faithful to him
b) Blameless
c) Perfect toward him
d) Righteous

204. According to 2 Chronicles 16:10, Asa was angry with the seer and put him in the stocks. Asa also oppressed some of the people at that time. In the thirty-ninth year of his reign, Asa was diseased in his feet. What did he do?
a) He repented
b) He sought the Lord
c) He did not seek the Lord, but sought help from physicians
d) He asked the priests to pray

205. According to 2 Chronicles 16:13, Asa died in the forty-first year of his reign. How long did he reign?
a) 30 years
b) 33 years
c) 41 years
d) 50 years

2 Chronicles 17 — Jehoshaphat’s Reforms
206. According to 2 Chronicles 17:3-4, the Lord was with Jehoshaphat because he walked in the first ways of his father David and did not seek the Baals, but sought the God of his father and walked in his commandments, and not according to the ways of Israel. What did he remove from Judah?
a) The high places
b) The Asherim
c) The golden calves
d) The foreign altars

207. According to 2 Chronicles 17:7-9, in the third year of his reign, Jehoshaphat sent his officials and the Levites to teach in the cities of Judah. What book did they have with them?
a) The Book of the Law of the Lord
b) The Psalms of David
c) The prophecies of Isaiah
d) The Proverbs of Solomon

208. According to 2 Chronicles 17:12-13, Jehoshaphat grew steadily greater. He built fortresses and store cities in Judah. He had large supplies in the cities of Judah and soldiers, mighty men of valor, in Jerusalem. How many mighty men of valor did the commanders of Judah have?
a) 100,000
b) 300,000
c) 780,000
d) 1,160,000

2 Chronicles 18 — Jehoshaphat Allies with Ahab
209. According to 2 Chronicles 18:1, Jehoshaphat had great riches and honor and made a marriage alliance with Ahab king of Israel. Who was Ahab’s daughter (or relative) that married Jehoshaphat’s son Jehoram?
a) Jezebel
b) Athaliah
c) Maacah
d) Zibiah

210. According to 2 Chronicles 18:3, Ahab king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, “Will you go with me to Ramoth-gilead?” Jehoshaphat said, “I am as you are, my people as your people. We will be with you in the war.” What did Jehoshaphat then ask?
a) “How many soldiers do you have?”
b) “Inquire first for the word of the Lord”
c) “What is the battle plan?”
d) “Will you pay me tribute?”

211. According to 2 Chronicles 18:5, the king of Israel gathered 400 prophets and asked, “Shall we go to battle?” They said, “Go up, for God will give it into the hand of the king.” Who were these 400 prophets?
a) Prophets of the Lord
b) Prophets of Baal and Asherah
c) False prophets of Ahab
d) Prophets from Judah

212. According to 2 Chronicles 18:6, Jehoshaphat asked, “Is there no other prophet of the Lord of whom we may inquire?” Ahab said, “There is one Micaiah the son of Imlah, but I hate him, for he never prophesies good concerning me but always evil.” What did Micaiah prophesy?
a) Victory for Ahab
b) Defeat and that Ahab would die
c) A draw
d) A temporary peace

213. According to 2 Chronicles 18:19-22, Micaiah saw a vision of the Lord on his throne. A lying spirit volunteered to be a lying spirit in the mouth of all Ahab’s prophets. This teaches what about false prophecy?
a) God permits deception as judgment
b) God causes all lies
c) Prophets are always reliable
d) Satan has no power

214. According to 2 Chronicles 18:33-34, a certain man drew his bow at random and struck the king of Israel between the scale armor and the breastplate. Ahab died that evening. This fulfilled whose prophecy?
a) Elijah’s
b) Elisha’s
c) Micaiah’s
d) Jehu’s

2 Chronicles 19 — Jehoshaphat’s Reforms After the Battle
215. According to 2 Chronicles 19:2, Jehu the son of Hanani the seer went out to meet Jehoshaphat and said, “Should you help the wicked and love those who hate the Lord? Because of this, wrath has gone out against you from the Lord. Nevertheless, some good is found in you, for you have removed what?”
a) The idols
b) The Asherim
c) The high places
d) The foreign priests

216. According to 2 Chronicles 19:5-7, Jehoshaphat appointed judges in all the fortified cities of Judah and said to them, “Consider what you do, for you judge not for man but for the Lord. He is with you in giving judgment. Now then, let the fear of the Lord be upon you; take heed what you do, for there is no perversion of justice with the Lord our God, or partiality, or taking of what?”
a) Gifts
b) Bribes
c) Favor
d) Oaths

217. According to 2 Chronicles 19:8-10, Jehoshaphat also appointed Levites, priests, and heads of families in Jerusalem for the judgment of the Lord and to decide controversies. He instructed them to warn the people not to trespass against the Lord. This system established what kind of legal structure?
a) Secular courts
b) Religious courts integrated with civil law
c) Military tribunals
d) Royal decrees only

2 Chronicles 20 — Jehoshaphat’s Prayer and Victory
218. According to 2 Chronicles 20:1, the Moabites, Ammonites, and some of the Meunites came to make war against Jehoshaphat. Where were they coming from?
a) The south
b) The east of the Dead Sea
c) The north
d) The wilderness of Zin

219. According to 2 Chronicles 20:3, Jehoshaphat was afraid and set his face to seek the Lord. He proclaimed a fast throughout all Judah. What did the people do?
a) They fled
b) They gathered together to seek help from the Lord
c) They prepared for war
d) They sent tribute to the invaders

220. According to 2 Chronicles 20:5-12, Jehoshaphat stood in the assembly of Judah and Jerusalem in the house of the Lord before the new court and prayed, “O Lord, God of our fathers, are you not God in heaven? You rule over all the kingdoms of the nations. In your hand are power and might, so that none is able to withstand you.” He recounted that when Israel came out of Egypt, God commanded them not to destroy Ammon, Moab, and Mount Seir. Therefore, these nations were now repaying Israel by driving them out of God’s possession. He concluded, “We are powerless against this great multitude, and we do not know what to do, but our eyes are upon whom?”
a) Our army
b) Our allies
c) You
d) The prophets

221. According to 2 Chronicles 20:14-15, the Spirit of the Lord came upon Jahaziel the Levite. He said, “Hearken, all Judah and inhabitants of Jerusalem, and King Jehoshaphat: Thus says the Lord to you, ‘Fear not, and be not dismayed at this great multitude; for the battle is not yours but God’s.’” Where was Jahaziel from within the Levitical families?
a) Kohathites
b) Gershomites
c) Asaphites
d) Merarites

222. According to 2 Chronicles 20:17, the Lord said, “You will not need to fight in this battle; take your position, stand still, and see the victory of the Lord on your behalf, O Judah and Jerusalem.” What were they to do the next day?
a) Go down against them
b) Wait in Jerusalem
c) Send spies
d) Build an altar

223. According to 2 Chronicles 20:21-22, Jehoshaphat appointed singers to sing to the Lord and praise him in holy array, saying, “Give thanks to the Lord, for his steadfast love endures forever.” As they began to sing and praise, the Lord set ambushes against the Ammonites, Moabites, and Mount Seir. What happened to the enemy armies?
a) They fled
b) They surrendered
c) They destroyed one another
d) They worshiped the Lord

224. According to 2 Chronicles 20:24, when Judah came to the watchtower of the wilderness, they looked toward the multitude and saw only dead bodies lying on the ground; none had escaped. How long did they take to gather the spoil?
a) One day
b) Three days
c) Seven days
d) Ten days

225. According to 2 Chronicles 20:29-30, the fear of God came upon all the kingdoms of the countries when they heard that the Lord had fought against the enemies of Israel. So the realm of Jehoshaphat was quiet, for his God gave him rest round about. What happened in the later part of Jehoshaphat’s reign (verse 35-37)?
a) He remained faithful
b) He made an alliance with Ahaziah king of Israel, who did wickedly
c) He built a second temple
d) He conquered Egypt

2 Chronicles 21 — Jehoram’s Evil Reign
226. According to 2 Chronicles 21:3, Jehoshaphat gave his sons great gifts of silver, gold, and fortified cities, but he gave the kingdom to Jehoram because he was the firstborn. After Jehoram became king, what did he do to his brothers?
a) He exiled them
b) He killed all his brothers with the sword
c) He imprisoned them
d) He sent them away with gifts

227. According to 2 Chronicles 21:6, Jehoram walked in the way of the kings of Israel, as the house of Ahab had done, for the daughter of Ahab was his wife. He did what was evil in the sight of the Lord. Who was Jehoram’s wife?
a) Athaliah (daughter of Ahab)
b) Jezebel
c) Maacah
d) Zibiah

228. According to 2 Chronicles 21:12-15, a letter came to Jehoram from Elijah the prophet (though Elijah had been taken up to heaven earlier — this is a chronological note in Chronicles). The letter said, “Because you have not walked in the ways of Jehoshaphat your father, but have walked in the way of the kings of Israel, and have led Judah into harlotry, and have killed your brothers, behold, the Lord will bring a great plague on your people, your children, your wives, and all your possessions, and you yourself will have a severe sickness of what?”
a) Leprosy
b) A disease of your bowels
c) Blindness
d) Paralysis

229. According to 2 Chronicles 21:18-19, after all this, the Lord struck Jehoram with an incurable disease of the bowels. He died in great agony, and his people made no fire in his honor, as had been done for his fathers. How old was Jehoram when he died?
a) 40 years
b) 30 years
c) 50 years
d) 32 years

2 Chronicles 22 — Ahaziah and Athaliah
230. According to 2 Chronicles 22:2, Ahaziah (also called Jehoahaz) was how old when he began to reign, and he reigned one year in Jerusalem?
a) 22 years
b) 42 years
c) 32 years
d) 20 years

231. According to 2 Chronicles 22:3-4, Ahaziah walked in the ways of the house of Ahab because his mother Athaliah was his counselor in doing wickedly. He did what was evil in the sight of the Lord. After Ahaziah went to visit Joram (Jehoram) king of Israel in Jezreel, what happened?
a) He was captured by Syria
b) He was killed by Jehu, whom the Lord anointed to destroy the house of Ahab
c) He died in battle
d) He repented

232. According to 2 Chronicles 22:10, when Athaliah the mother of Ahaziah saw that her son was dead, she arose and did what?
a) She fled to Egypt
b) She destroyed all the royal offspring of the house of Judah
c) She made peace with Jehu
d) She took the throne

233. According to 2 Chronicles 22:11, Jehoshabeath (or Jehosheba), the daughter of King Jehoram and sister of Ahaziah, took Joash the son of Ahaziah and hid him from Athaliah in the house of God. Who was the husband of Jehoshabeath?
a) Jehoiada the priest
b) Zechariah
c) Azariah
d) Urijah

2 Chronicles 23 — Joash Crowned and Athaliah Killed
234. According to 2 Chronicles 23:1, in the seventh year, Jehoiada the priest showed his strength and made a covenant with the commanders of hundreds. He brought them into the house of the Lord, showed them the king’s son, and organized a coup. On the Sabbath day, what did the guards do?
a) They rested
b) They guarded the temple and crowned Joash
c) They arrested Athaliah
d) They fled

235. According to 2 Chronicles 23:11, they brought out the king’s son (Joash), put the crown on him, gave him the testimony, and made him king. Then they anointed him. What did the people do?
a) They shouted, “Long live the king!”
b) They wept
c) They offered sacrifices
d) They ran to their homes

236. According to 2 Chronicles 23:12-13, Athaliah heard the noise of the people running and praising the king. She went into the house of the Lord and saw the king standing by his pillar at the entrance, with the captains and trumpeters, and all the people rejoicing. What did Athaliah do?
a) She bowed down
b) She tore her clothes and cried, “Treason! Treason!”
c) She fled
d) She ordered the guards to attack

237. According to 2 Chronicles 23:15, they put Athaliah to death at the entrance of the horse gate of the king’s house. What happened to the house of Baal that Athaliah had built?
a) It became a temple to the Lord
b) They tore it down and broke its altars and images
c) It was left standing
d) It was given to the priests

2 Chronicles 24 — Joash’s Reign and Apostasy
238. According to 2 Chronicles 24:1, Joash was seven years old when he began to reign, and he reigned forty years in Jerusalem. His mother’s name was Zibiah of Beersheba. As long as Jehoiada the priest lived, Joash did what was right in the eyes of the Lord. What was one of Joash’s major projects?
a) Building a palace
b) Repairing the house of the Lord
c) Building a new altar
d) Fortifying Jerusalem

239. According to 2 Chronicles 24:15-16, Jehoiada the priest grew old and died at 130 years. He was buried among the kings because he had done good in Israel and toward God. After Jehoiada’s death, the princes of Judah came and did homage to Joash. What did Joash do?
a) He remained faithful
b) He listened to them, and they forsook the house of the Lord and served Asherim and idols
c) He built a new temple
d) He made war with Israel

240. According to 2 Chronicles 24:20-21, the Spirit of God came upon Zechariah the son of Jehoiada the priest. He stood above the people and said, “Why do you transgress the commandments of the Lord? Because you have forsaken the Lord, he has forsaken you.” What did the people do to Zechariah?
a) They repented
b) They conspired against him and stoned him at the command of the king in the court of the house of the Lord
c) They arrested him
d) They exiled him

241. According to 2 Chronicles 24:22, Joash did not remember the kindness which Jehoiada had shown him but killed his son. As Zechariah was dying, he said, “May the Lord see and avenge!” What happened to Joash at the end of his reign?
a) He died in peace
b) The Syrians invaded, and Joash was wounded and then killed by his own servants
c) He was taken captive to Babylon
d) He abdicated the throne

2 Chronicles 25 — Amaziah’s Reign
242. According to 2 Chronicles 25:2, Amaziah did what was right in the eyes of the Lord, but not with a what?
a) Whole heart
b) Perfect heart
c) Blameless heart
d) Faithful heart

243. According to 2 Chronicles 25:5-6, Amaziah assembled Judah and hired 100,000 mighty men of valor from Israel for 100 talents of silver. However, a man of God came to him and said, “Do not let the army of Israel go with you, for the Lord is not with Israel.” What did Amaziah do?
a) He ignored the prophet
b) He sent the Israelites back, though he lost the 100 talents
c) He attacked without them
d) He asked for a sign

244. According to 2 Chronicles 25:11-12, Amaziah defeated the Edomites in the Valley of Salt and took Sela (Petra). He threw 10,000 Edomites down from a rock. After the victory, Amaziah brought back the gods of the men of Seir and set them up as his gods. What happened when he worshiped them?
a) He prospered
b) God sent a prophet to rebuke him, and Amaziah threatened the prophet
c) He was immediately struck with leprosy
d) He lost his throne

245. According to 2 Chronicles 25:17-22, Amaziah challenged Jehoash king of Israel to battle. Jehoash warned him that his pride would cause his downfall. They met at Beth-shemesh, and Judah was defeated. What happened to Amaziah?
a) He was killed
b) He was captured, and the wall of Jerusalem was broken down
c) He fled to Egypt
d) He made peace

2 Chronicles 26 — Uzziah’s Reign and Pride
246. According to 2 Chronicles 26:5, Uzziah (Azariah) set himself to seek God in the days of Zechariah, who instructed him in the fear of God. As long as he sought the Lord, God made him prosper. What did Uzziah build in Jerusalem?
a) The temple
b) Engines of war invented by skillful men
c) A palace
d) A new city wall

247. According to 2 Chronicles 26:16, when Uzziah was strong, he grew proud to his destruction. He was unfaithful to the Lord and went into the temple of the Lord to burn incense on the altar of incense. Which group of 81 priests confronted him?
a) The Levites
b) The sons of Aaron (the priests)
c) The gatekeepers
d) The prophets

248. According to 2 Chronicles 26:19-20, Uzziah was angry with the priests, and while he was angry, leprosy broke out on his forehead. He remained a leper until the day he died, living in a separate house. Who reigned as regent?
a) His son Jotham
b) His wife
c) The high priest
d) His brother

2 Chronicles 27 — Jotham’s Reign
249. According to 2 Chronicles 27:2, Jotham did what was right in the eyes of the Lord according to all that his father Uzziah did, but he did not enter the temple of the Lord. What did the people still do?
a) They worshiped the Lord faithfully
b) They continued acting corruptly
c) They built high places
d) They made treaties with Assyria

250. According to 2 Chronicles 27:3-4, Jotham built the upper gate of the house of the Lord and built extensively on the wall of Ophel. He also built cities in the hill country of Judah and fortresses and towers in the wooded areas. How long did he reign?
a) 10 years
b) 16 years
c) 20 years
d) 25 years

2 Chronicles 28 — Ahaz’s Idolatry and Punishment
251. According to 2 Chronicles 28:2-3, Ahaz walked in the ways of the kings of Israel and made molten images for the Baals. He burned incense in the Valley of the Son of Hinnom and burned his sons as an offering according to the abominable practices of the nations. What did the Lord do?
a) He blessed Ahaz
b) He gave him into the hand of the king of Syria and the king of Israel
c) He sent prophets to warn him
d) He destroyed Jerusalem immediately

252. According to 2 Chronicles 28:9-11, Oded the prophet met the army of Israel returning with 200,000 captives from Judah. He said, “Because the Lord was angry with Judah, he gave them into your hand, but you have slaughtered them in a rage which has reached heaven. Now hear me, send back the captives.” What did the leaders of Israel do?
a) They refused
b) They released the captives and clothed and fed them
c) They killed Oded
d) They kept the captives as slaves

253. According to 2 Chronicles 28:22-25, in his time of distress, Ahaz became more unfaithful to the Lord. He sacrificed to the gods of Damascus, saying, “Because the gods of the kings of Syria helped them, I will sacrifice to them that they may help me.” He also shut up the doors of the house of the Lord. What did he do in every city of Judah?
a) He built high places to burn incense to other gods
b) He built synagogues
c) He destroyed the idols
d) He fortified the walls

2 Chronicles 29 — Hezekiah’s Reforms
254. According to 2 Chronicles 29:2-3, Hezekiah did what was right in the eyes of the Lord according to all that David his father had done. In the first year of his reign, in the first month, he opened the doors of the house of the Lord and repaired them. Why had the doors been shut?
a) The Assyrians had destroyed them
b) Ahaz had shut them
c) The priests had locked them out of fear
d) An earthquake had sealed them

255. According to 2 Chronicles 29:5, Hezekiah said to the Levites, “Sanctify yourselves, and sanctify the house of the Lord, the God of your fathers, and carry out the filth from the holy place. For our fathers have been unfaithful and have done what was evil in the sight of the Lord.” What was the first thing they did?
a) They offered sacrifices
b) They removed the defiled things from the temple
c) They sang praises
d) They anointed the altar

256. According to 2 Chronicles 29:27-28, when the burnt offering began, the song to the Lord began also, accompanied by trumpets and instruments of David. The whole assembly worshiped, and the singers sang, and the trumpeters sounded. How long did this continue?
a) Until the burnt offering was finished
b) Three days
c) Seven days
d) Until sunset

257. According to 2 Chronicles 29:30-31, Hezekiah and the princes commanded the Levites to sing praises to the Lord with the words of David and Asaph the seer. They sang with gladness, and they bowed down and worshiped. How many burnt offerings did the assembly bring?
a) 100 bulls, 200 sheep, 400 lambs
b) 70 bulls, 100 rams, 200 lambs
c) 1,000 bulls, 2,000 rams, 10,000 lambs
d) 50 bulls, 50 rams, 50 lambs

2 Chronicles 30 — The Passover Restored
258. According to 2 Chronicles 30:1, Hezekiah sent to all Israel and Judah and wrote letters to Ephraim and Manasseh inviting them to come to the house of the Lord at Jerusalem to keep the Passover. To whom did he also write?
a) The king of Assyria
b) The remnant who had escaped the kings of Assyria
c) The priests of Baal
d) The Egyptians

259. According to 2 Chronicles 30:5-6, the couriers went throughout all Israel and Judah with letters from the king and his princes, as the king had commanded, saying, “O people of Israel, return to the Lord, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel, that he may turn again to the remnant of you who have escaped from the hand of the kings of Assyria.” What did many people do when they received the invitation?
a) They mocked the couriers
b) They humbled themselves and came to Jerusalem
c) They killed the couriers
d) They ignored the invitation

260. According to 2 Chronicles 30:18-20, many people from Ephraim, Manasseh, Issachar, and Zebulun had not purified themselves yet ate the Passover. Hezekiah prayed for them, saying, “May the good Lord pardon everyone who sets his heart to seek God, though not according to the sanctuary’s rules of cleanness.” What did the Lord do?
a) He struck them with plague
b) He healed the people and heard Hezekiah
c) He rejected their offering
d) He sent a prophet to rebuke them

261. According to 2 Chronicles 30:26, there was great joy in Jerusalem, for since the time of Solomon the son of David king of Israel there had been nothing like this in Jerusalem. The priests and Levites blessed the people, and their voice was heard. Who heard their prayer?
a) The king
b) The people
c) Heaven, God’s holy habitation
d) The angels

2 Chronicles 31 — Hezekiah’s Further Reforms
262. According to 2 Chronicles 31:1, after the Passover, all Israel went out to the cities of Judah and broke the pillars, cut down the Asherim, and threw down the high places and altars throughout Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh. Then the people returned to their cities. What did Hezekiah then restore?
a) The army
b) The divisions of the priests and Levites for offerings and tithes
c) The walls of Jerusalem
d) The trade routes

263. According to 2 Chronicles 31:4-5, Hezekiah commanded the people to give the portion due to the priests and Levites. When the command was spread abroad, the people brought in abundance the first fruits of grain, wine, oil, honey, and all the produce of the field. For how many months did they heap up the offerings?
a) One month
b) Four months (from the third to the seventh month)
c) Six months
d) Twelve months

2 Chronicles 32 — Sennacherib’s Invasion and Hezekiah’s Sickness
264. According to 2 Chronicles 32:1, after these faithful deeds, Sennacherib king of Assyria came and invaded Judah and encamped against the fortified cities, thinking to win them for himself. How did Hezekiah respond?
a) He surrendered
b) He stopped the water springs outside the city and built up the wall
c) He fled to Egypt
d) He sent tribute

265. According to 2 Chronicles 32:7-8, Hezekiah encouraged the people, saying, “Be strong and of good courage. Do not be afraid or dismayed before the king of Assyria and all the horde that is with him, for there is a greater power with us than with him. With him is an arm of flesh; but with us is the Lord our God, to help us and to fight our battles.” This echoes the words of which earlier leader?
a) Moses
b) Joshua
c) David
d) Jehoshaphat

266. According to 2 Chronicles 32:20-21, Hezekiah and Isaiah the prophet prayed and cried to heaven. The Lord sent an angel who cut off all the mighty warriors and commanders in the camp of the king of Assyria. Sennacherib returned to his own land with shame. How did he die?
a) In battle
b) He was killed by his own sons with the sword
c) He died of plague
d) He drowned in a river

267. According to 2 Chronicles 32:24-25, Hezekiah became sick and was at the point of death. He prayed to the Lord, and the Lord answered him and gave him a sign. But Hezekiah did not make return according to the benefit done to him, for his heart was proud. What happened as a result?
a) He lost his kingdom
b) Wrath came upon him and Judah and Jerusalem
c) His son was taken captive
d) He died immediately

268. According to 2 Chronicles 32:31, God left Hezekiah to himself to test him and to know all that was in his heart. What was the occasion? When envoys of the princes of Babylon sent to inquire of the sign that had been done in the land, Hezekiah showed them all his treasures. What was the result?
a) Babylon became friendly
b) Isaiah prophesied that all would be carried to Babylon
c) Hezekiah repented
d) The treasures were stolen

2 Chronicles 33 — Manasseh’s Wickedness and Repentance
269. According to 2 Chronicles 33:2-6, Manasseh did what was evil in the sight of the Lord. He rebuilt the high places, built altars for the Baals, made Asherim, worshiped all the host of heaven, burned his sons as an offering in the Valley of Hinnom, practiced soothsaying, and consulted mediums. What did he do in the house of the Lord?
a) He cleansed it
b) He built altars for all the host of heaven in the two courts of the house of the Lord
c) He tore it down
d) He offered sacrifices

270. According to 2 Chronicles 33:11, the Lord brought the commanders of the army of the king of Assyria against Manasseh. What did they do to him?
a) They killed him
b) They took him with hooks, bound him with fetters, and brought him to Babylon
c) They made him pay tribute
d) They made him a slave

271. According to 2 Chronicles 33:12-13, when Manasseh was in distress, he entreated the favor of the Lord his God and humbled himself greatly before the God of his fathers. He prayed to him, and God was entreated and heard his plea and brought him back to Jerusalem. Then Manasseh knew that the Lord was God. What did Manasseh do after his return?
a) He returned to idolatry
b) He removed the foreign gods and the idols and restored the altar of the Lord
c) He built a new temple
d) He abdicated the throne

272. According to 2 Chronicles 33:15-16, Manasseh took away the foreign gods and the idol from the house of the Lord and all the altars he had built. He repaired the altar of the Lord and sacrificed peace offerings and thank offerings on it. What did he command Judah to do?
a) To serve the Lord God of Israel
b) To pay taxes
c) To build the wall
d) To make peace with Assyria

2 Chronicles 34 — Josiah’s Reforms
273. According to 2 Chronicles 34:1-2, Josiah was eight years old when he began to reign, and he reigned thirty-one years in Jerusalem. He did what was right in the eyes of the Lord and walked in the ways of David. In the eighth year of his reign, while he was yet young, he began to seek the God of David. In the twelfth year, he began to purge Judah and Jerusalem of what?
a) The Assyrian garrisons
b) The high places, Asherim, graven images, and molten images
c) The foreign merchants
d) The corrupt priests

274. According to 2 Chronicles 34:8, in the eighteenth year of his reign, Josiah sent Shaphan son of Azaliah, Maaseiah the governor of the city, and Joah son of Joahaz the recorder to repair the house of the Lord his God. What was found in the temple during the repairs?
a) The ark of the covenant
b) The book of the law of the Lord given through Moses
c) The golden lampstand
d) The staff of Aaron

275. According to 2 Chronicles 34:14-15, Hilkiah the priest found the book of the law of the Lord. He gave it to Shaphan the secretary, who read it. Then Shaphan brought it to the king and read it before him. When Josiah heard the words of the law, what did he do?
a) He rejoiced
b) He tore his clothes
c) He burned the book
d) He ignored it

276. According to 2 Chronicles 34:22-25, Josiah sent to Huldah the prophetess, the wife of Shallum, who lived in Jerusalem. She said, “Thus says the Lord: Behold, I will bring evil upon this place and upon its inhabitants, all the curses written in the book. Because they have forsaken me and burned incense to other gods, my wrath will be poured out. But because your heart was penitent and you humbled yourself before God when you heard his words, you shall be gathered to your grave in peace, and your eyes shall not see the evil I will bring.” What did Josiah do after this?
a) He doubted
b) He gathered all the elders and read the book to them and made a covenant before the Lord
c) He fled to Egypt
d) He built a new altar

2 Chronicles 35 — Josiah Keeps the Passover
277. According to 2 Chronicles 35:1, Josiah kept a Passover to the Lord in Jerusalem. The Passover lamb was killed on the fourteenth day of the first month. When was the last time such a Passover had been celebrated?
a) In the days of Hezekiah
b) In the days of Samuel
c) In the days of Solomon
d) In the days of David

278. According to 2 Chronicles 35:18, no Passover like it had been kept in Israel since the days of Samuel the prophet, and none of the kings of Israel had kept such a Passover as Josiah kept, with the priests, Levites, all Judah and Israel present, and the inhabitants of Jerusalem. Who was the king of Egypt who came up to fight at Carchemish?
a) Shishak
b) Pharaoh Necho
c) Taharqa
d) Rameses II

279. According to 2 Chronicles 35:20-22, Josiah went out to fight Necho at Megiddo. Necho sent messengers to Josiah saying, “What have we to do with each other, king of Judah? I am not coming against you this day, but against the house with which I am at war; and God has commanded me to make haste. Cease opposing God, who is with me, lest he destroy you.” How did Josiah respond?
a) He turned back
b) He did not listen to Necho but disguised himself and fought
c) He made a treaty
d) He prayed for guidance

280. According to 2 Chronicles 35:23-24, the archers shot King Josiah, and he was wounded. He died in Jerusalem and was buried in the tombs of his fathers. All Judah and Jerusalem mourned for Josiah. Jeremiah uttered a lament for Josiah. What became a regular practice in Israel?
a) The singing of dirges
b) The reading of the law
c) The Passover celebration
d) The burning of incense

2 Chronicles 36 — The Fall of Jerusalem and the Exile
281. According to 2 Chronicles 36:3-4, after Josiah’s death, the people made Jehoahaz (also called Shallum) king. Pharaoh Necho deposed him, fined Judah 100 talents of silver and a talent of gold, and made whom king in his place?
a) Jehoiakim (Eliakim)
b) Zedekiah
c) Jeconiah
d) Mattaniah

282. According to 2 Chronicles 36:5-6, Jehoiakim did what was evil. Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came up against him, bound him in fetters, and took him to Babylon. Nebuchadnezzar also carried off some of the vessels of the house of the Lord to Babylon. Who reigned next?
a) Jehoiachin (Jeconiah) — he reigned three months
b) Zedekiah
c) Josiah again
d) Mattaniah

283. According to 2 Chronicles 36:11-12, Zedekiah (Mattaniah) was twenty-one years old when he began to reign, and he reigned eleven years. He did what was evil in the sight of the Lord. He did not humble himself before Jeremiah the prophet who spoke from the mouth of the Lord. What else did he do?
a) He rebelled against Nebuchadnezzar
b) He made a treaty with Egypt
c) He burned the temple
d) He killed the priests

284. According to 2 Chronicles 36:15-16, the Lord sent messengers persistently to his people because he had compassion on them. But they mocked the messengers of God, despised his words, and scoffed at his prophets, until the wrath of the Lord rose against his people until there was no remedy. Who came up against them?
a) The Assyrians
b) The Chaldeans (Babylonians)
c) The Egyptians
d) The Edomites

285. According to 2 Chronicles 36:17-20, the Chaldeans burned the house of God, broke down the wall of Jerusalem, burned all its palaces, destroyed all its precious vessels, and carried off to Babylon those who survived the sword. They were servants to Nebuchadnezzar and his sons until the kingdom of Persia came to power. How long did the land enjoy its sabbath rests?
a) 70 years
b) 50 years
c) 40 years
d) 30 years

286. According to 2 Chronicles 36:22-23, in the first year of Cyrus king of Persia, the Lord stirred up the spirit of Cyrus to make a proclamation throughout all his kingdom. He said, “Who is there among you of all his people? The Lord his God be with him. Let him go up to Jerusalem and build the house of the Lord, the God of Israel.” This fulfilled what prophecy?
a) The prophecy of Isaiah
b) The prophecy of Jeremiah
c) The prophecy of Ezekiel
d) The prophecy of Hosea

