PART 2 — THEORY QUESTIONS (100)
(Answers Separated at the End)
1 Chronicles 1–9 (Genealogies)
287. Why do the genealogies in 1 Chronicles 1–9 begin with Adam and go through Abraham, Israel, and Judah specifically? What theological purpose do they serve for the post-exilic community?

288. According to 1 Chronicles 4:9-10, what was the prayer of Jabez? What does his inclusion in the genealogies teach about God’s response to faithful prayer?

289. In 1 Chronicles 5:1-2, why did Reuben lose his birthright, and to whom was it given? How does this relate to the prominence of Judah and Joseph in later history?

290. According to 1 Chronicles 6:31-48, David appointed Levites as musicians before the ark. How does this establish the importance of worship music in Israel’s temple tradition?

1 Chronicles 10 — The Death of Saul
291. According to 1 Chronicles 10:13-14, what two specific sins led to Saul’s death? How does the Chronicler’s explanation differ from the account in 1 Samuel?

292. Why does the Chronicler begin his narrative of the monarchy with Saul’s death rather than his reign? What lesson about obedience to God is emphasized?

1 Chronicles 11 — David’s Mighty Men
293. In 1 Chronicles 11:15-19, three mighty men risked their lives to bring David water from Bethlehem. Why did David refuse to drink it? What does this teach about leadership and sacrifice?

294. According to 1 Chronicles 11:22-23, describe the exploits of Benaiah son of Jehoiada. What made him one of David’s most honored mighty men?

1 Chronicles 12 — David’s Supporters
295. According to 1 Chronicles 12:32, the men of Issachar had understanding of the times to know what Israel should do. Why is this spiritual discernment important for leadership?

296. How does 1 Chronicles 12:38-40 describe the unity of all Israel in making David king? What does this teach about national unity under God’s anointed?

1 Chronicles 13 — The Ark
297. In 1 Chronicles 13:7-10, why did the Lord strike Uzzah dead for touching the ark? What principle about God’s holiness and proper worship is taught here?

298. How did David react to Uzzah’s death, and where did he take the ark instead of Jerusalem? What lesson did David learn about the proper way to transport the ark?

1 Chronicles 14 — David’s Victories
299. In 1 Chronicles 14:8-17, how did David inquire of the Lord before each battle against the Philistines? What does this teach about seeking God’s guidance?

300. According to 1 Chronicles 14:14-15, what specific instruction did God give for the second battle? How is the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees interpreted?

1 Chronicles 15 — The Ark Brought to Jerusalem
301. According to 1 Chronicles 15:2, what did David learn from the Uzzah incident about who should carry the ark? How did he correct his previous error?

302. Describe the worship procession of the ark in 1 Chronicles 15:16-28. What roles did the Levites, singers, and David himself play?

1 Chronicles 16 — The Ark in Jerusalem
303. According to 1 Chronicles 16:7-36, David appointed Asaph and his brethren to give thanks. List at least four themes from this psalm of thanksgiving.

304. 1 Chronicles 16:34 says, “Give thanks to the Lord, for he is good; his steadfast love endures forever.” How does this refrain shape Israel’s worship throughout the Psalms?

1 Chronicles 17 — God’s Covenant with David
305. In 1 Chronicles 17:1-15, David wanted to build a house for God, but God said David’s son would build it. What did God promise to build for David instead? How is this fulfilled?

306. According to 1 Chronicles 17:13-14, God said of Solomon, “I will be his father, and he shall be my son; I will not take my steadfast love from him as I took it from Saul.” How does this point toward the eternal Davidic kingdom in Jesus Christ?

1 Chronicles 18–20 — David’s Wars
307. According to 1 Chronicles 18:6 and 18:13, what phrase is repeated to describe David’s military success? Who gave him these victories?

308. In 1 Chronicles 19:1-5, why did Hanun humiliate David’s servants, and what was the result? What does this teach about responding to kindness with suspicion?

309. Describe the giant-killing exploits in 1 Chronicles 20:4-8. Who killed Goliath’s brother Lahmi, and who killed the six-fingered giant?

1 Chronicles 21 — The Census and the Plague
310. According to 1 Chronicles 21:1, who incited David to number Israel? In 2 Samuel 24:1, it says the Lord’s anger was kindled against Israel and he incited David. How do you reconcile these two accounts?

311. In 1 Chronicles 21:16-18, David saw the angel of the Lord standing between earth and heaven with a drawn sword. What did David say, and where did the angel stand? Why did David choose to fall into the hand of God rather than man?

312. According to 1 Chronicles 21:24, David refused to offer to God what cost him nothing. What did he pay for the threshing floor, and why is this principle important for worship?

1 Chronicles 22 — Preparations for the Temple
313. According to 1 Chronicles 22:5-16, why was David not permitted to build the temple, and what preparations did he make for Solomon to build it?

314. In 1 Chronicles 22:8-9, God promised that Solomon would be a man of peace. Why was the temple to be built in a time of peace rather than war?

1 Chronicles 23–27 — The Levitical Divisions
315. According to 1 Chronicles 23:3-5, how were the 38,000 Levites distributed among different duties? What does this organization reveal about the importance of order in worship?

316. According to 1 Chronicles 24:1-19, how were the priests divided into 24 courses, and why was the lot used to determine their service?

317. According to 1 Chronicles 25:1-7, what were the three families of musicians (Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun), and how many skilled musicians were trained?

1 Chronicles 28–29 — David’s Final Charge
318. In 1 Chronicles 28:2-7, David declared his desire to build the temple but was refused. What did David say about the temple as a “house of rest” for the ark?

319. According to 1 Chronicles 28:9, David charged Solomon to know God and serve him with a whole heart. What does “the Lord searches all hearts” mean for leaders today?

320. In 1 Chronicles 29:10-20, summarize David’s prayer of praise. What does he say about God’s ownership of all things and the nature of human giving?

321. According to 1 Chronicles 29:28, David died at a good old age. What does the Chronicler say about the sources for David’s acts (Samuel, Nathan, Gad)?

2 Chronicles 1 — Solomon’s Wisdom
322. In 2 Chronicles 1:7-12, when God said “Ask what I shall give you,” why did Solomon ask for wisdom rather than wealth or long life? How did God reward his choice?

2 Chronicles 2–4 — Building the Temple
323. According to 2 Chronicles 2:13-14, what were the skills of Huram-abi the craftsman? How does this show the excellence of work offered to God?

324. Describe the molten sea (bronze basin) in 2 Chronicles 4:2-6. What was its size, capacity, and purpose? What did the ten smaller lavers do?

2 Chronicles 5–7 — Dedication of the Temple
325. According to 2 Chronicles 5:13-14, when the musicians praised God, the house was filled with a cloud. What did this cloud represent, and why could the priests not stand to minister?

326. In 2 Chronicles 6:12-42, Solomon’s prayer of dedication includes seven petitions. Name at least four of them (e.g., oath between men, defeat in battle, drought, foreigner, etc.).

327. According to 2 Chronicles 7:12-14, what was God’s conditional promise to heal the land? What four actions must the people take?

328. In 2 Chronicles 7:19-22, what warning did God give about turning away to serve other gods? What would happen to the temple and the people?

2 Chronicles 8–9 — Solomon’s Glory
329. According to 2 Chronicles 9:1-8, what did the Queen of Sheba come to see, and what was her reaction to Solomon’s wisdom and the temple?

330. What was the annual weight of gold that came to Solomon (2 Chronicles 9:13)? What does this say about the wealth and peace of his kingdom?

2 Chronicles 10 — Division of the Kingdom
331. In 2 Chronicles 10:6-14, why did Rehoboam reject the counsel of the old men and follow the young men’s advice? What was the fatal result?

332. According to 2 Chronicles 10:15, the king did not hearken to the people “for it was a turn of affairs brought about by God.” How does this verse show God’s sovereignty even over human rebellion?

2 Chronicles 11–12 — Rehoboam
333. In 2 Chronicles 12:1-4, when Rehoboam and Judah were unfaithful, who attacked them? What did Shemaiah the prophet say, and how did they respond?

334. According to 2 Chronicles 12:7-8, God relented from destroying Judah because they humbled themselves, but they became servants to Shishak. What did they learn through this judgment?

2 Chronicles 13 — Abijah
335. In 2 Chronicles 13:4-12, what argument did Abijah make against Jeroboam and the northern kingdom regarding the legitimate priesthood and temple?

336. How did Judah win the battle against Jeroboam (2 Chronicles 13:13-18)? What role did the priests’ trumpets play?

2 Chronicles 14–16 — Asa
337. In 2 Chronicles 14:9-12, when Zerah the Ethiopian came against Asa with 1,000,000 men, what was Asa’s prayer, and how did God answer?

338. According to 2 Chronicles 16:1-9, when Baasha king of Israel attacked, Asa relied on Ben-hadad of Syria instead of the Lord. What did Hanani the seer say to Asa, and how did Asa respond?

339. What happened to Asa in his old age (2 Chronicles 16:12-14), and what lesson does his failure teach?

2 Chronicles 17–20 — Jehoshaphat
340. According to 2 Chronicles 17:7-9, what did Jehoshaphat do in the third year of his reign to teach the law throughout Judah? How did this strengthen the kingdom?

341. In 2 Chronicles 18, Jehoshaphat allied with Ahab and went to battle. Why did he insist on inquiring of a prophet of the Lord? What was Micaiah’s prophecy?

342. According to 2 Chronicles 20:3-12, when the Moabites and Ammonites attacked, what did Jehoshaphat pray? What did he mean by “We do not know what to do, but our eyes are upon you”?

343. In 2 Chronicles 20:21-25, how did the Lord give victory without Judah fighting? What happened when the singers praised the Lord?

2 Chronicles 21–24 — Jehoram, Ahaziah, Athaliah, Joash
344. According to 2 Chronicles 21:12-15, what did Elijah’s letter say to Jehoram? What disease did he die from?

345. In 2 Chronicles 22:10-12 and 23:1-15, how did Athaliah seize the throne, and how was she overthrown by Jehoiada the priest?

346. According to 2 Chronicles 24:17-22, after Jehoiada died, Joash listened to the princes and forsook the Lord. Zechariah the son of Jehoiada prophesied against them. How did Joash respond, and what was his end?

2 Chronicles 25–26 — Amaziah and Uzziah
347. In 2 Chronicles 25:5-13, Amaziah hired Israelite soldiers but sent them away at the prophet’s command. What did the prophet promise, and what happened to the dismissed soldiers?

348. According to 2 Chronicles 26:16-21, what was Uzziah’s sin? Why was he struck with leprosy even though he had been a good king?

2 Chronicles 27–28 — Jotham and Ahaz
349. According to 2 Chronicles 28:22-25, how did Ahaz respond to his distress? What did he do to the temple and the altars in Jerusalem?

2 Chronicles 29–32 — Hezekiah
350. In 2 Chronicles 29:3-11, what did Hezekiah do in the first month of his reign? What did he say to the priests and Levites about the unfaithfulness of their fathers?

351. According to 2 Chronicles 30:18-20, how did Hezekiah pray for the northern Israelites who ate the Passover without proper purification? How did the Lord answer?

352. According to 2 Chronicles 32:7-8, how did Hezekiah encourage the people when Sennacherib besieged Jerusalem? What was the greater power with them?

353. In 2 Chronicles 32:24-26, Hezekiah became proud after his recovery. What happened as a result, and how did he humble himself?

2 Chronicles 33 — Manasseh
354. According to 2 Chronicles 33:11-16, what happened to Manasseh when he was taken captive to Babylon? How did he respond, and what did he do when God brought him back?

355. What does Manasseh’s repentance teach about the possibility of forgiveness for the worst sins?

2 Chronicles 34–35 — Josiah
356. According to 2 Chronicles 34:14-21, what was found in the temple during repairs, and how did Josiah react when it was read to him?

357. In 2 Chronicles 34:22-28, what message did Huldah the prophetess give to Josiah? Why would he not see the coming disaster?

358. According to 2 Chronicles 35:20-24, why did Josiah go out to fight Pharaoh Necho at Megiddo? What were the consequences of ignoring Necho’s warning?

2 Chronicles 36 — The Fall of Jerusalem
359. According to 2 Chronicles 36:15-16, what did God do before bringing judgment? How did the people respond to the prophets?

360. In 2 Chronicles 36:17-21, describe the destruction of Jerusalem and the temple. How long did the exile last, and what prophecy did it fulfill?

361. According to 2 Chronicles 36:22-23, what did Cyrus king of Persia decree? How does this show God’s sovereignty over foreign kings?

General/Review Questions
362. Trace the theme of “seeking the Lord” through Chronicles (e.g., Asa, Jehoshaphat, Hezekiah, Josiah, Manasseh’s repentance). What happens when kings seek the Lord versus when they do not?

363. How does the Chronicler treat the northern kingdom of Israel? Why does he focus almost exclusively on Judah and the Davidic line?

364. What is the role of the prophets in Chronicles (e.g., Shemaiah, Azariah, Hanani, Jehu, Jahaziel, Oded, Huldah)? How do they call kings to obedience?

365. According to Chronicles, why was the temple built in Jerusalem? How does the temple serve as the center of Israel’s worship and national identity?

366. Compare the account of David’s census in 1 Chronicles 21 with 2 Samuel 24. What theological emphases does the Chronicler add or change?

367. How does the Chronicler portray the relationship between worship (music, sacrifice, prayer) and military victory (e.g., Jehoshaphat in 2 Chronicles 20)?

368. According to 2 Chronicles 7:14, what is the formula for national healing? How has this verse been applied in various historical contexts?

369. What does Chronicles teach about God’s patience and mercy (e.g., sending prophets repeatedly, forgiving Manasseh, relenting from destroying Jerusalem)?

370. How does the genealogy from Adam to Abraham to David to the post-exilic community in Chronicles 1–9 affirm God’s faithfulness to his covenant promises?

371. According to Chronicles, what is the most important qualification for a king? Give examples of kings who succeeded and failed in this regard.

372. How does the Chronicler’s emphasis on the temple, the priesthood, and proper worship address the needs of the post-exilic community returning from Babylon?

373. What does the prayer of Jabez (1 Chronicles 4:10) reveal about the relationship between personal faith, divine blessing, and protection from harm?

374. In 2 Chronicles 18 (Jehoshaphat and Ahab), what does the vision of the lying spirit teach about divine sovereignty over false prophets and deception?

375. According to 2 Chronicles 6:18, Solomon said, “Heaven and the highest heaven cannot contain you.” How does this transcendence of God relate to his immanence in the temple?

376. In 2 Chronicles 20:20, Jehoshaphat said, “Believe in the Lord your God, and you will be established; believe his prophets, and you will succeed.” How does this summarize the message of Chronicles?

377. Compare the repentance of Manasseh (2 Chronicles 33) with the hard-heartedness of Ahaz (2 Chronicles 28). What made the difference?

378. According to 2 Chronicles 12:14, “He did evil, for he did not set his heart to seek the Lord.” How does the condition of the heart determine a king’s legacy?

379. What does the detailed organization of the priests, Levites, gatekeepers, and musicians in 1 Chronicles 23–27 teach about the importance of order and preparation in worship?

380. How does the Chronicler use the phrase “the Lord was with him” (e.g., Jehoshaphat, Hezekiah) to explain success? What causes the Lord to leave a king?

381. According to 2 Chronicles 15:2, Azariah told Asa, “The Lord is with you while you are with him. If you seek him, he will be found by you, but if you forsake him, he will forsake you.” How does this conditional promise shape the theology of Chronicles?

382. What does the story of Joash (2 Chronicles 24) teach about the danger of good leaders who only follow God while a godly mentor (Jehoiada) is alive?

383. According to 2 Chronicles 25:2, Amaziah did what was right but not with a whole heart. What does “half-hearted obedience” lead to in his story?

384. How does the Chronicler justify the long reign of evil kings (e.g., Manasseh) and the short reigns of some good kings (e.g., Josiah’s tragic death)?

385. Why does the Chronicler end with Cyrus’s decree (2 Chronicles 36:22-23) rather than with the destruction of Jerusalem? What hope does this ending provide?

386. According to 1 Chronicles 17, God’s promise to David includes an eternal throne. How does this point beyond the historical kings of Judah to the Messiah?

387. How does the Chronicler handle the sins of David (Bathsheba and Uriah) compared to 2 Samuel? Why might he omit or soften certain details?

388. In 2 Chronicles 33:19, Manasseh’s prayer of repentance is recorded (though not in Kings). What does the Chronicler include that 2 Kings omits about Manasseh?

389. How does the Chronicler portray the relationship between the temple and the king? Who has authority over the temple — the king or the priests?

390. What is the significance of the “covenant of salt” in 2 Chronicles 13:5? Why does Abijah use this term to argue for David’s dynasty?

391. According to 2 Chronicles 1:10, Solomon asked for wisdom to govern the people. How does this request reflect the ideal of a shepherd-king?

392. How does the Chronicler’s account of Hezekiah’s Passover (2 Chronicles 30) include the northern tribes? What does this say about the hope for a reunited Israel?

393. According to 2 Chronicles 19:5-7, Jehoshaphat appointed judges and told them, “You judge not for man but for the Lord.” How does this elevate the concept of justice?

394. What does the story of Uzziah’s leprosy (2 Chronicles 26:16-21) teach about the boundary between royal and priestly functions?

395. How does the Chronicler treat the subject of repentance even after judgment (e.g., Manasseh, and the people who returned from exile)?

396. According to 2 Chronicles 31:20-21, Hezekiah prospered because he did what was good, right, and faithful, and he sought his God with his whole heart. How does this summarize the formula for success in Chronicles?

397. Why does the Chronicler include the long lists of names (genealogies, warriors, officials) when other biblical books omit them? What purpose do they serve for the original audience?

398. Compare the account of Sennacherib’s defeat in 2 Chronicles 32:20-22 with 2 Kings 19. What details does the Chronicler emphasize or omit?

399. According to 2 Chronicles 22:3-4, Ahaziah’s mother Athaliah was his counselor in doing wickedly. How does Chronicles highlight the influence of family and marriage alliances on a king’s faithfulness?

400. Summarize the main theological message of 1 and 2 Chronicles in one paragraph. How does it answer the question, “Does God still have a future for his people after the exile?”

✅ ANSWERS TO THEORY QUESTIONS (287–400)
(Answers provided in summary form. For full biblical responses, consult the RSV text.)

287. Genealogies connect the post-exilic community to God’s promises from Adam to Abraham to David, showing that God has preserved a remnant and that the promises remain valid despite the exile.

288. Jabez prayed, “Oh that you would bless me and enlarge my border, and that your hand might be with me, and that you would keep me from harm so that it might not hurt me.” God granted what he asked. It teaches that God responds to sincere, specific prayer.

289. Reuben defiled his father’s bed; the birthright went to Joseph (by genealogy), but Judah became the ruling tribe. This establishes Judah’s preeminence for the Davidic line.

290. It establishes that worship through music is a divinely ordained part of temple service, led by trained Levites, and that praise precedes and accompanies sacrifice.

291. Unfaithfulness to the Lord and consulting a medium. The Chronicler emphasizes Saul’s failure to seek God properly, leading to his death.

292. To show that the monarchy begins properly only with David, God’s chosen king, while Saul serves as a negative example of disobedience.

293. David poured it out as an offering to the Lord because it was the blood of men who risked their lives. He valued their lives more than his thirst.

294. Benaiah killed two lions of Moab, killed an Egyptian giant with his own spear, and killed a lion in a pit on a snowy day.

295. Discernment to know God’s will for the times is essential for national and spiritual leadership, especially in seasons of transition.

296. All Israel came with united heart to make David king, eating and drinking in fellowship for three days — a picture of national unity under God’s anointed.

297. Uzzah touched the ark irreverently. The ark was holy and was to be carried only by Levites with poles, not on a cart. God’s holiness demands proper worship.

298. David was angry and afraid, leaving the ark at Obed-edom’s house. He learned that the ark must be carried by Levites with poles.

299. David inquired of the Lord twice before each battle, not relying on past victories. He waited for specific divine direction.

300. God told David to circle around and come upon them opposite the balsam trees, attacking when he heard the sound of marching in the treetops — the signal that God had gone before him.

301. David learned that only Levites should carry the ark, as the Lord had commanded Moses. He corrected the error by having Levites carry it with poles.

302. The Levites carried the ark, singers and musicians played harps, lyres, cymbals, and trumpets, and David danced and wore a linen ephod. The whole assembly brought up the ark with shouting and music.

303. (1) Call to sing and declare God’s glory among the nations; (2) Remember his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, Jacob; (3) Worship in holy array; (4) Give thanks for his steadfast love.

304. It became the central refrain of temple worship, reminding Israel that God’s covenant love is the foundation of all praise, repeated in Psalms 100, 106, 107, 118, 136.

305. God promised to build David a house (dynasty) — an eternal throne. This is fulfilled in Jesus Christ, the Son of David, whose kingdom is forever.

306. The promise of an unbroken dynasty finds ultimate fulfillment in Christ, who reigns forever. God’s steadfast love is never removed from David’s line in Christ.

307. “The Lord gave victory to David wherever he went.” Victory comes from the Lord, not from military might alone.

308. Hanun humiliated David’s messengers because he listened to bad advice, leading to war. Responding to kindness with suspicion destroys relationships.

309. Elhanan killed Lahmi (Goliath’s brother), and Jonathan, son of Shimea, killed the six-fingered giant.

310. In Chronicles, Satan incites David; in Samuel, the Lord’s anger incites him. This reflects divine sovereignty (God permits testing) and secondary causation (Satan acts as the immediate tempter).

311. David said, “I have sinned greatly.” The angel stood at the threshing floor of Ornan. David chose to fall into God’s hand because God’s mercy is great.

312. He paid 600 shekels of gold. Worship must involve genuine sacrifice, not cheap or convenient offerings.

313. David was a man of war who shed blood. He prepared gold, silver, bronze, iron, timber, and stone in abundance for Solomon to build.

314. The temple, as a house of rest for God’s name, symbolizes peace. It could only be built in a time of peace, pointing to the Prince of Peace.

315. 24,000 for temple work, 6,000 officers/judges, 4,000 gatekeepers, 4,000 singers. Order reflects God’s nature and ensures proper worship.

316. 24 courses determined by lot to ensure fairness. The lot was a way of seeking God’s will without human favoritism.

317. Asaph, Heman (Korahite), Jeduthun. 288 skilled musicians, trained and equal with their brethren.

318. A house of rest for the ark (God’s footstool). David’s desire was good, but God chose a different builder.

319. God knows every thought and motive. Leaders must serve with integrity, knowing they cannot hide anything from God.

320. God owns all things; humans give back what is already God’s. David praises God’s greatness and asks for a wholehearted devotion for Solomon.

321. 40 years. Chronicler cites Samuel, Nathan, and Gad as prophetic sources, showing that prophecy accompanied David’s reign.

322. Solomon prioritized ruling God’s people well over personal gain. God rewarded him with both wisdom and unprecedented wealth/honor.

323. Huram-abi was skilled in gold, silver, bronze, iron, stone, wood, and purple/blue fabrics. Excellence honors God.

324. 10 cubits diameter, 30 cubits circumference, held 3,000 baths. For priests to wash. Ten lavers washed offerings.

325. The cloud was the glory-cloud (Shekinah) of God’s presence. The priests could not stand because the glory was overwhelming.

326. (1) Oaths between men; (2) Defeat in battle; (3) Drought; (4) Plague; (5) Foreigner praying toward temple; (6) Israel going to war; (7) Captivity and repentance.

327. (1) Humble themselves; (2) Pray; (3) Seek God’s face; (4) Turn from wicked ways. Then God will hear, forgive, and heal the land.

328. God will uproot Israel from the land and reject the temple, making it a proverb and a byword among all peoples.

329. The Queen came to test Solomon’s wisdom, saw his prosperity and the temple, and declared that even half was not told her. She praised Solomon’s God.

330. 666 talents of gold. It shows the extraordinary peace, prosperity, and extent of Solomon’s kingdom as a type of God’s blessing.

331. Pride and the arrogance of youth. Rehoboam wanted to assert his authority harshly, causing the kingdom to split.

332. God sovereignly overruled Rehoboam’s foolishness to fulfill the prophecy through Ahijah about the division of the kingdom (1 Kings 11).

333. Shishak of Egypt attacked. Shemaiah said, “You have abandoned me, so I have abandoned you.” They humbled themselves, saying, “The Lord is righteous.”

334. They learned the difference between serving God and serving earthly kingdoms. God’s discipline was merciful, not total destruction.

335. God gave the kingdom to David forever; Jeroboam’s golden calves rejected the true God; only the Aaronic priests and Levites in Jerusalem are legitimate.

336. Judah cried out to the Lord, the priests sounded the trumpets, and God routed Jeroboam. Victory came through worship and trust, not numbers.

337. Asa prayed, “Lord, help us for we rely on you.” God defeated the Ethiopians, and Judah carried away much spoil.

338. Hanani said, “You relied on Syria, not the Lord. You have done foolishly.” Asa was angry, put Hanani in stocks, and oppressed the people.

339. Asa developed a foot disease but sought physicians, not the Lord. He died after 41 years, his later years marked by failure.

340. He sent Levites to teach the Book of the Law throughout Judah. This brought stability and blessing.

341. Jehoshaphat insisted on hearing a true prophet, not just false ones. Micaiah prophesied defeat and Ahab’s death, which occurred.

342. Jehoshaphat acknowledged Judah’s powerlessness and confessed total dependence on God. The prayer is a model of humble trust.

343. As singers praised, God set ambushes against the enemy, who destroyed each other. Judah only collected spoil for three days.

344. Because Jehoram killed his brothers and led Judah into idolatry, Elijah’s letter prophesied a great plague and Jehoram’s death from a bowel disease.

345. Athaliah killed all royal heirs; Jehoshabeath hid Joash. Jehoiada crowned Joash, and Athaliah was executed at the horse gate.

346. Joash stoned Zechariah in the temple court. Later, Joash was defeated by the Syrians and killed by his own servants.

347. The prophet said God was not with Israel. Those dismissed soldiers raided Judah’s cities later, showing the consequences of disobedience.

348. Uzziah entered the temple to burn incense, a priestly duty. God struck him with leprosy for usurping the priesthood.

349. Ahaz became more unfaithful, sacrificed to Syrian gods, shut the temple doors, and built altars in every corner of Jerusalem.

350. He opened and repaired the temple doors. He said, “Our fathers have been unfaithful and turned their backs on God.”

351. Hezekiah prayed, “Lord pardon everyone who sets his heart to seek God.” The Lord healed the people.

352. “With us is the Lord our God to fight our battles.” The greater power is God himself, not the arm of flesh.

353. Wrath came upon Judah and Jerusalem. Hezekiah humbled himself, and the wrath did not come in his days.

354. Manasseh was taken to Babylon with hooks and fetters. He prayed, God brought him back, and he removed idols and restored the altar.

355. Even the worst sinner who truly repents can find mercy. God delights in forgiveness.

356. The Book of the Law. Josiah tore his clothes in grief because of the curses written in the book.

357. The disaster would come, but because Josiah humbled himself, he would be buried in peace and not see it.

358. Josiah disguised himself to fight Necho despite Necho’s claim that God commanded him. He was fatally wounded at Megiddo.

359. God sent prophets persistently with compassion. The people mocked them until wrath was unavoidable.

360. The Chaldeans burned the temple, broke down the wall, and carried off survivors. The 70-year exile fulfilled Jeremiah’s prophecy, giving the land its sabbaths.

361. Cyrus decreed that Jews could return to Jerusalem and rebuild the temple, fulfilling Isaiah’s prophecy (Isaiah 44:28).

362. When kings seek the Lord, they prosper; when they forsake him, disaster comes. Repentance (Manasseh) can restore blessing.

363. The northern kingdom is largely ignored because their worship was illegitimate (golden calves) and they rejected the Davidic dynasty. Chronicles focuses on Judah as the true Israel.

364. Prophets confront kings, call for repentance, announce judgment, and guide in times of crisis. They are God’s mouthpiece to the monarchy.

365. The temple is the place of God’s name, the ark, the altar, and legitimate sacrifice. It unites worship, law, and national identity.

366. Chronicles adds Satan as the tempter and emphasizes God’s mercy in stopping the plague at the threshing floor of Ornan, the future temple site.

367. Worship and prayer precede and accompany battle. Jehoshaphat’s singers went first; God fought for them. Worship is a weapon.

368. National healing requires humility, prayer, seeking God, and repentance. It has been used in calls for national revival.

369. God sends prophets repeatedly, forgives Manasseh, and relents from destroying Jerusalem when people humble themselves. Mercy triumphs over judgment.

370. The genealogies show unbroken continuity from creation to the post-exilic community, affirming that God’s covenant promises remain faithful despite the exile.

371. Wholehearted seeking of the Lord. Examples: David, Jehoshaphat, Hezekiah, Josiah succeed; Saul, Rehoboam, Ahaz fail.

372. The emphasis reassures the returned exiles that proper worship (temple, priesthood, sacrifices) is restored and that God is still with them.

373. Personal faith invites God’s blessing and protection, but blessing should not be mistaken for earned merit. It is grace.

374. God sovereignly uses even deception as judgment on those who reject the truth. This passage is difficult but affirms God’s ultimate control.

375. God transcends all creation yet chooses to dwell with his people in a special way in the temple. Immanence does not negate transcendence.

376. Faith in God and trust in his prophets (true messengers) leads to establishment and success. Unbelief leads to failure.

377. Manasseh humbled himself when afflicted; Ahaz became more defiant. Response to discipline distinguishes them.

378. The heart’s direction determines the whole life. Outward actions follow inward commitment — or lack thereof.

379. Worship must be orderly, prepared, and excellent. Spontaneity without preparation can lead to irreverence (Uzzah).

380. The Lord is with those who seek him and obey him. He departs when kings are unfaithful, leaving them vulnerable.

381. God’s presence is conditional on Israel’s faithfulness. This is a deuteronomic (covenant-based) theology: obedience brings blessing, disobedience brings curse.

382. Joash followed God only while Jehoiada mentored him. After Jehoiada died, Joash listened to evil advisors, showing the need for personal, sustained faith.

383. Half-hearted obedience leads to pride (Amaziah worshiped Edom’s gods) and eventual downfall. God desires whole hearts, not partial compliance.

384. The Chronicler measures reigns by faithfulness, not length. Even a short good reign (Josiah) is valuable; a long evil reign (Manasseh) still ends in judgment (though Manasseh repented).

385. The book ends with hope: God stirs Cyrus to restore the temple and people. The exile is not the final word; restoration is coming.

386. The eternal throne finds ultimate fulfillment in Jesus, the Son of David, who reigns forever over a spiritual kingdom.

387. The Chronicler omits David’s sin with Bathsheba and Uriah, perhaps to present David as a model king for the post-exilic community, focusing on his positive legacy.

388. The Chronicler includes Manasseh’s prayer of repentance and his restoration, showing that even the worst king can be forgiven.

389. Priests have authority over temple worship; kings may provide for and organize the temple but cannot perform priestly functions (Uzziah’s sin).

390. A covenant of salt means a permanent, binding covenant. Abijah argues that David’s dynasty is eternally established by God.

391. The ideal king is a shepherd who serves the people, not himself. Wisdom enables righteous governance.

392. The invitation to the north shows the Chronicler’s hope for a reunited Israel under proper worship in Jerusalem.

393. Justice is a divine mandate, not merely human legislation. Judges act as God’s representatives and must reflect his character.

394. The king may be a civil and military leader, but priestly duties belong exclusively to the descendants of Aaron. Crossing this boundary brings judgment.

395. Repentance is always possible, even after judgment begins (Manasseh) or after exile (Cyrus’s decree). God is merciful.

396. Wholehearted seeking of God, faithful obedience to the law, and doing what is good and right bring divine blessing and prosperity.

397. Lists establish identity, continuity, and legitimacy. For the post-exilic community, knowing one’s genealogy connected them to the covenant promises.

398. The Chronicler emphasizes Hezekiah’s prayer and Isaiah’s prophecy, the angel’s slaughter of the Assyrian army, and Sennacherib’s death by his sons.

399. Foreign alliances and marriages often led to idolatry. Chronicles warns against unholy partnerships that corrupt faith.

400. God remains faithful to his covenant with David despite Israel’s unfaithfulness and exile. He preserves a remnant, restores worship, and promises an eternal throne. The future hope is rooted in repentance and seeking the Lord
